               <head>Book of Breathing made by Isis for her brother Osiris.</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>Fragments of a funerary text, known as the Book of Breathing, written for
                     a certain man called Kephalon, son of Tanakau, with illustrations.</summary>
                  <textLang mainLang="egy-Egyh">Egyptian in Hieratic script</textLang>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="scroll">
                     <supportDesc material="papyrus">
                        <support/>
                        <extent>Fragments of the upper part of an almost complete papyrus roll
                           written along the fibres with the back being blank. The papyrus is
                           mounted on paper and housed in two glass cases. The lower half of the
                           papyrus is preserved at the British Musuem in London as <ref
                              target="https://www.britishmuseum.org/collection/object/Y_EA10260-1"
                              >EA10260,1</ref> and<ref
                              target="https://www.britishmuseum.org/collection/object/Y_EA10260-2"
                              >EA10260,2</ref>
                           <dimensions type="frame1" n="1" unit="mm">
                              <height>125</height>
                              <width>565</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="frame2" n="2" unit="mm">
                              <height>125</height>
                              <width>565</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>Written in 3 columns preceded by an illustration panel.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>Likely written by one scribe, all in black ink.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>The papyrus opens with a coloured illustration panel showing the
                        introduction of the deceased Kephalon by a priest or Anubis to an enthroned
                        Osiris under a green hieroglyph of the sky. Behind Osiris's throne there are
                        the standing figures of Horus, Nephthys and Isis but only their heads are
                        preserved, the lower half of the figures are on the fragments at the British
                        Museum in London.</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>


               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Gregorian" notBefore="-0199" notAfter="-0001">199-1
                        BC</origDate></origin>
                  <provenance>Possibly from <ref type="place_7001297">Thebes</ref>. Purchased by
                     Colonel Valentine Patrick Terrell Vivian in Egypt around 1882 and bequeathed to
                     his brother-in-law the Reverend Vivian Eccles Skrine. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>Given to the Bodleian by the Reverend Vivian Eccles Skrine
                     (1850-1925), 30 March 1913.</acquisition>
               </history>
